 gland","Glans clitoris","Bulb of vestibule","Crus of clitoris","Labia majora"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ecrus of clitoris\u003C/strong\u003E consists of paired erectile tissue that attaches to the ischiopubic rami and joins in the midline to form part of the body of the clitoris. The \u003Cstrong\u003Egreater vestibular glands\u003C/strong\u003E (Bartholin\u0027s glands) are paired secretory structures located in the deep perineal pouch. The \u003Cstrong\u003Eglans clitoris\u003C/strong\u003E is the sensitive tip of the clitoris covered by the prepuce. The \u003Cstrong\u003Ebulb of vestibule\u003C/strong\u003E is paired erectile tissue located on either side of the vaginal opening. The \u003Cstrong\u003Elabia majora\u003C/strong\u003E are the outer skin folds of the vulva.\u003C/p\u003E        \u003Cp\u003EThe crus of clitoris is homologous to the crus penis in males, both being composed of erectile tissue and serving as the deep attachments of their respective organs to the pubic arch.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The crus of clitoris consists of paired erectile tissue that forms the deep roots of the clitoris, attaching to the pubic arch.","The female erectile tissues are homologous to male erectile tissues, with the crus clitoris corresponding to the crus penis."],"references":["Puppo V. Anatomy of the Clitoris: Revision and Clarifications about the Anatomical Terms for the Clitoris Proposed (without Scientific Bases) by Helen O\u0027Connell, Emmanuele Jannini, and Odile Buisson. ISRN Obstet Gynecol. 2011;2011:261464. doi: 10.5402/2011/261464. Epub 2011 Sep 15. PMID: 21941661; PMCID: PMC3175415.","Evans, T. J., \u0026 Ganjam, V. K. (2017). Reproductive anatomy and physiology. In Reproductive and Developmental Toxicology (pp. 7-37). Academic Press","Bolla SR, Hoare BS, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Abdomen and Pelvis: Deep Perineal Space. [Updated 2023 Aug 8]. 